more resistant to anoikis, as you

256
00:14:27.748 --> 00:14:30.828
can see here. And also importantly, you can see that

257
00:14:31.768 --> 00:14:35.208
mTOR signaling under the conditions of detachment,

258
00:14:36.068 --> 00:14:37.128
which is here,

259
00:14:38.008 --> 00:14:41.868
is reduced, as you can see, by phosphorylation of these downstream substrates

260
00:14:41.928 --> 00:14:43.288
of mTORC1.

261
00:14:44.448 --> 00:14:48.288
So we decided then to see what the mechanism here could

262
00:14:48.348 --> 00:14:51.388
be. And to do so, we compared the

263
00:14:52.028 --> 00:14:55.748
transcript and wide changes in translation, that are also known

264
00:14:55.808 --> 00:14:57.148
as translatome,

265
00:14:58.188 --> 00:15:01.288
between the attached and detached cells that are either

266
00:15:01.948 --> 00:15:05.788
4E-BP1 deficient or proficient. And this led

267
00:15:05.828 --> 00:15:08.698
us to another surprise. So not only that 4E-BP1,

268
00:15:10.228 --> 00:15:13.668
that it didn't make much sense that 4E-BP1 as tumor

269
00:15:13.748 --> 00:15:17.548
suppressor is increasing the number of metastases or is actually

270
00:15:17.588 --> 00:15:21.148
required for metastasis. 4E-BP1 is also a translational

271
00:15:21.208 --> 00:15:25.088
suppressor, but we could see actually translational upregulation

272
00:15:25.268 --> 00:15:29.188
of a number of mRNAs, most of which were involved in

273
00:15:29.228 --> 00:15:33.128
the processes that are actually implicated in the early steps of

274
00:15:33.148 --> 00:15:36.688
metastasis, such as migration, invasion, and anoikis

275
00:15:36.748 --> 00:15:40.248
resistance. And one of those was pannexin 1,

276
00:15:40.908 --> 00:15:44.648
that plays a major role in the matrix cell contacts

277
00:15:44.848 --> 00:15:48.088
and interactions through ATP and calcium signaling.

278
00:15:48.968 --> 00:15:52.768
So Pedja went to test what else could be

279
00:15:52.828 --> 00:15:56.428
there, and here it was observed that

280
00:15:57.348 --> 00:16:00.708
mRNAs that the translation upregulated upon detachment

281
00:16:01.448 --> 00:16:04.848
in 4E-BP1 proficient cells, so those whose translation is

282
00:16:05.688 --> 00:16:06.868
4E-BP1 dependent,

283
00:16:08.148 --> 00:16:10.248
and their synthesis is upregulated,

284
00:16:11.208 --> 00:16:14.978
actually have much longer five prime UTRs,

285
00:16:15.148 --> 00:16:19.008
as you can see here. And they also have a

286
00:16:19.068 --> 00:16:22.137
higher proportion of upstream open reading frames that are relatively

287
00:16:22.188 --> 00:16:23.128
well-established

288
00:16:24.348 --> 00:16:27.828
translational control elements in their five prime untranslated

289
00:16:27.888 --> 00:16:28.388
regions.

290
00:16:29.208 --> 00:16:32.768
So this led us to think that these features of the mRNAs

291
00:16:32.868 --> 00:16:36.068
somehow make these

292
00:16:37.188 --> 00:16:40.187
transcripts translation upregulated under conditions

293
00:16:41.308 --> 00:16:44.588
where 4E-BP is actually activated and translation should be

294
00:16:44.888 --> 00:16:45.488
inhibited.

295
00:16:47.348 --> 00:16:51.248
And then it was decided that we should validate pannexin

296
00:16:51.568 --> 00:16:55.268
1, and you can see that the protein levels of pannexin 1 are

297
00:16:55.348 --> 00:16:59.328
upregulated in the cells that are 4E-BP1 proficient compared

298
00:16:59.388 --> 00:17:03.328
to those that lack 4E-BP1. There are two

299
00:17:03.408 --> 00:17:07.229
bands here because there is a cleavage product that's recognized with these

300
00:17:07.238 --> 00:17:08.368
antibodies, so they're both

301
00:17:10.648 --> 00:17:14.588
originating from pannexin. And there was no change in the RNA

302
00:17:14.608 --> 00:17:17.278
levels of pannexin, thus further suggesting that this

303
00:17:18.189 --> 00:17:22.168
increase in pannexin 1 protein levels is indeed occurring at the level

304
00:17:22.229 --> 00:17:26.148
of mRNA translation. And then if you deplete

305
00:17:26.158 --> 00:17:29.858
pannexin 1, this invasive advantage of

306
00:17:29.988 --> 00:17:33.728
cells that are 4E-BP1 proficient was actually diminished,

307
00:17:35.348 --> 00:17:39.228
whereas pannexin 1 didn't have that much effect on the cells that didn't

308
00:17:39.268 --> 00:17:42.548
express 4E-BP1. So this indicated that

309
00:17:43.068 --> 00:17:43.888
4E-BP1,

310
00:17:44.908 --> 00:17:48.888
pannexin axis is involved in stimulation of these early

311
00:17:48.928 --> 00:17:49.368
steps

312
00:17:50.268 --> 00:17:53.808
or stimulation of progression of cells through the early steps of metastatic

313
00:17:53.828 --> 00:17:54.428
cascade.

314
00:17:56.228 --> 00:18:00.148
But we still couldn't understand what's going on and why

315
00:18:00.328 --> 00:18:04.248
4LN mutant that's constitutively active didn't work better than the

316
00:18:04.288 --> 00:18:04.948
wild type.

317
00:18:05.868 --> 00:18:08.608
And this led us to think about this rheostat model.

318
00:18:09.188 --> 00:18:13.048
But it's easy to think, it's much harder to prove, but Pedja

319
00:18:13.108 --> 00:18:16.748
is excellent. So he came up with this experiment

320
00:18:17.408 --> 00:18:20.952
whereby he would sort of dosemTOR

321
00:18:20.962 --> 00:18:24.832
signaling by stimulating cells with serum and then monitoring what

322
00:18:24.892 --> 00:18:27.272
happens to pannexin-1 protein levels.

323
00:18:27.832 --> 00:18:31.272
And you can see here when he starts adding serum,

324
00:18:31.892 --> 00:18:35.472
that pannexin-1 peaks before mTOR signaling

325
00:18:35.552 --> 00:18:39.372
is maximally activated, thus indicating that

326
00:18:39.452 --> 00:18:42.432
this translational increase in pannexin-1

327
00:18:43.192 --> 00:18:43.952
requires

328
00:18:44.932 --> 00:18:45.652
not too much,

329
00:18:46.552 --> 00:18:50.492
but a little bit of mTOR signaling, some

330
00:18:50.512 --> 00:18:52.772
sort of a Goldilocks zone, if you will, and so on.

331
00:18:53.512 --> 00:18:57.452
When you continue stimulating cells with serum and further induce mTOR

332
00:18:57.492 --> 00:18:57.972
signaling,

333
00:18:58.892 --> 00:19:02.132
the pannexin-1 levels go down, and then if you inhibit

334
00:19:02.812 --> 00:19:06.312
mTOR signaling by this mTORc1-specific inhibitor,

335
00:19:07.472 --> 00:19:09.552
pannexin-1 is reduced again.

336
00:19:10.492 --> 00:19:13.992
And then he did a similar experiment with mTOR inhibitors, where he just dosed the

337
00:19:14.012 --> 00:19:16.572
levels of mTOR inhibitors, and he observed the same thing.

338
00:19:18.132 --> 00:19:21.852
In this concentration gradient, there was a dose of

339
00:19:21.972 --> 00:19:25.852
mTORc1 that induced pannexin-1, and before and after,

340
00:19:26.452 --> 00:19:28.032
the levels of pannexin-1 were lower.

341
00:19:28.132 --> 00:19:31.492
So, this led us also to think that

342
00:19:32.232 --> 00:19:36.152
just inhibiting mTORc1 may not stimulate metastasis, which

343
00:19:36.192 --> 00:19:37.192
would be

344
00:19:38.392 --> 00:19:42.132
sort of advantageous considering that some of these drugs are in the clinic.

345
00:19:42.822 --> 00:19:46.492
And indeed, that happens if you put mTOR inhibitors and

346
00:19:46.532 --> 00:19:48.872
inhibit mTORc1 almost completely.

347
00:19:48.972 --> 00:19:50.742
So strong inhibition of mTORc1

348
00:19:52.852 --> 00:19:56.632
sort of decreased the invasion potential of the 4E-BP1

349
00:19:56.672 --> 00:19:58.792
proficient cells, as you can see here.

350
00:19:59.672 --> 00:20:03.512
So this led us to this model whereby the stressors that

351
00:20:03.572 --> 00:20:07.172
act across metastatic cascade, of which there are many,

352
00:20:07.952 --> 00:20:11.732
tune mTORc1 activity to the point that the

353
00:20:11.772 --> 00:20:15.712
translatomes are going to be remodeled in 4E-BP1-dependent manner in a way

354
00:20:15.752 --> 00:20:19.432
that favors metastasis. And this also

355
00:20:19.472 --> 00:20:22.532
allows cells to switch between proliferative and

356
00:20:23.032 --> 00:20:25.032
metastatic proteomes, if you will,

357
00:20:26.092 --> 00:20:29.852
because proliferation needs to stop in order for

358
00:20:29.892 --> 00:20:33.252
cells to migrate, invade, and survive in oicus,

359
00:20:35.132 --> 00:20:35.892
meaning survive in

360
00:20:37.352 --> 00:20:41.132
the circulation. And then it needs to be reactivated once they

361
00:20:41.172 --> 00:20:45.092
go to the secondary site and need to grow metastasis or secondary

362
00:20:45.132 --> 00:20:45.492
tumors.

363
00:20:46.372 --> 00:20:49.952
And we do think that this is a major

364
00:20:50.732 --> 00:20:54.472
mechanism that's implicated in metastasis, and we think that this is

365
00:20:54.532 --> 00:20:58.492
how protein synthesis is implicated in this process.

366
00:20:58.652 --> 00:21:02.052
Of course, we still don't understand the precise mechanism.

367
00:21:02.822 --> 00:21:05.972
Maybe I shouldn't have said, of course, but we don't understand the precise

368
00:21:06.072 --> 00:21:10.012
mechanism of how these mRNAs, such

369
00:21:10.092 --> 00:21:13.552
as the one encoding pannexin, are upregulated under these

370
00:21:13.592 --> 00:21:15.832
conditions. But we are working on it.

371
00:21:16.432 --> 00:21:16.732
And

372
00:21:18.332 --> 00:21:21.632
in the sake of time, I won't get to this last point here.

373
00:21:21.642 --> 00:21:24.992
It turns out, which was the third surprise in this project,

374
00:21:25.652 --> 00:21:29.512
that these effects are specific to 4E-BP1 and not its

375
00:21:29.572 --> 00:21:33.432
very close parallel, 4E-BP2, whereby it was thought that these two

376
00:21:33.512 --> 00:21:37.332
proteins have completely redundant functions and can

377
00:21:37.472 --> 00:21:38.652
substitute for each other.

378
00:21:39.852 --> 00:21:40.792
But in conclusion,

379
00:21:41.712 --> 00:21:41.772
I

380
00:21:42.832 --> 00:21:45.652
would say that-- And this all come from Peija.

381
00:21:45.732 --> 00:21:48.872
I did very little here. This was all driven by him.

382
00:21:48.992 --> 00:21:52.212
He's an extraordinarily talented PhD student.

383
00:21:54.012 --> 00:21:57.872
That although 4E-BP1s may be tumor suppressive when it comes

384
00:21:57.932 --> 00:21:59.932
to primary tumors, they

385
00:21:59.992 --> 00:22:03.772
stimulate metastasis,

386
00:22:04.392 --> 00:22:05.592
so there is this kind of

387
00:22:06.692 --> 00:22:10.352
antagonistic pleiotropism. You need 4E-BP1s

388
00:22:10.652 --> 00:22:14.612
not to be very active when the primary tumor grows, but then you have to tune them

389
00:22:14.712 --> 00:22:15.052
down

390
00:22:15.872 --> 00:22:17.932
in order for cells to metastasize.

391
00:22:19.352 --> 00:22:22.852
We think that this rheostat that's dialed by

392
00:22:22.932 --> 00:22:25.292
mTORc1 and centered on 4E-BP1,

393
00:22:26.412 --> 00:22:30.212
enables cells to switch from proliferative to metastatic states, and this

394
00:22:30.232 --> 00:22:32.192
doesn't require any changes in

395
00:22:33.992 --> 00:22:37.732
genomes of the cancer cells that would make them stuck in one or the other

396
00:22:37.871 --> 00:22:41.272
state, but allows them to sort of exhibit enough

397
00:22:41.311 --> 00:22:43.902
plasticity in order to move through metastatic cascade.

398
00:22:45.112 --> 00:22:48.582
And finally, we think that this occurs by

399
00:22:48.672 --> 00:22:52.552
upregulation, by paradoxical upregulation, I should say,

400
00:22:53.112 --> 00:22:54.532
of the mRNAs

401
00:22:55.392 --> 00:22:58.492
that's 4E-BP1 dependent. And with that,

402
00:22:59.532 --> 00:23:03.212
I would like just to thank all the collaborators and the

