00:28:25.320 --> 00:28:28.980
But the idea there was that there's slight

507
00:28:29.140 --> 00:28:32.940
differences between certain motifs within

508
00:28:32.960 --> 00:28:36.080
4E-BP1 and 2 that could explain maybe this way.

509
00:28:36.140 --> 00:28:39.580
So we are trying to switch them as they did back in the day,

510
00:28:39.860 --> 00:28:43.400
in this yeast reconstitute system, and we're hoping to find something

511
00:28:43.460 --> 00:28:47.280
here. And again, I shouldn't take any congratulations for this work

512
00:28:47.320 --> 00:28:51.040
because the only thing I was saying is that nothing makes sense, and Pedja should

513
00:28:51.060 --> 00:28:53.440
really be congratulated and the other people in the lab.

514
00:28:54.020 --> 00:28:57.040
And with that, thank you all. So next we have

515
00:29:01.440 --> 00:29:05.260
Professor Ole Larsen, who decided to take his tag

516
00:29:05.360 --> 00:29:08.240
off, but I know him. It's Ole Larsen there.

517
00:29:09.300 --> 00:29:12.440
And he's going to be talking about the dicodon

518
00:29:12.540 --> 00:29:16.300
organization and how it links the RNA modification to

519
00:29:16.760 --> 00:29:18.720
cancer cell proteome. All yours.

520
00:29:20.200 --> 00:29:23.880
Right. So thank you very much to the organizers for

521
00:29:24.120 --> 00:29:27.260
the invitation to come here and present some of our work that

522
00:29:27.860 --> 00:29:28.220
is

523
00:29:29.840 --> 00:29:32.100
completely unpublished, so this is really new stuff.

524
00:29:34.800 --> 00:29:36.340
So I have no disclosures.

525
00:29:37.900 --> 00:29:39.940
So Ivan already showed you this

526
00:29:41.300 --> 00:29:45.200
kind of figure that outlines the different steps of the gene expression

527
00:29:46.160 --> 00:29:50.060
pathway. So what I would like to emphasize again is that each of these

528
00:29:50.120 --> 00:29:53.520
mechanisms will, under certain conditions,

529
00:29:53.560 --> 00:29:57.100
contribute to establishment of the proteome.

530
00:29:57.600 --> 00:30:01.040
And we often talk about the translate, which is really the

531
00:30:01.940 --> 00:30:05.700
sort of the subset of the mRNAs that are efficiently translated.

532
00:30:09.060 --> 00:30:12.280
So when translation is regulated,

533
00:30:12.720 --> 00:30:16.700
this has two effects. So one effect

534
00:30:16.760 --> 00:30:20.480
you can think about is if you have different genes within the same

535
00:30:20.520 --> 00:30:24.420
cells. So different genes, they will not produce necessarily the same number

536
00:30:24.480 --> 00:30:28.460
of proteins per mRNA molecule. So this sort

537
00:30:28.800 --> 00:30:32.660
of allows the translation process to control

538
00:30:32.700 --> 00:30:35.440
relative protein production within a

539
00:30:35.500 --> 00:30:39.272
cell.But what we more often talk about, and what

540
00:30:39.712 --> 00:30:43.332
Ivan was also talking about, is the dynamic regulation, where you can

541
00:30:43.412 --> 00:30:46.792
change the translation of individual mRNAs to tune

542
00:30:46.852 --> 00:30:47.432
protein

543
00:30:48.332 --> 00:30:48.752
levels.

544
00:30:49.632 --> 00:30:53.392
And this happens then, for example, between different disease context, but

545
00:30:53.452 --> 00:30:56.902
also, of course, during normal physiological responses.

546
00:30:59.372 --> 00:31:02.992
Ivan was talking about translation initiation,

547
00:31:03.852 --> 00:31:07.332
but usually you talk about three different steps

548
00:31:07.492 --> 00:31:11.312
during and the translation process, where initiation involves the

549
00:31:11.552 --> 00:31:14.812
association with ribosomes with the mRNA,

550
00:31:15.392 --> 00:31:18.952
their scanning, and identification of the start

551
00:31:19.012 --> 00:31:22.472
site. This is then followed by the elongation phase, when

552
00:31:22.532 --> 00:31:24.941
the protein is synthesized, and

553
00:31:25.972 --> 00:31:27.152
finally termination.

554
00:31:29.972 --> 00:31:30.432
A key

555
00:31:32.152 --> 00:31:36.092
molecule during the elongation phase is the tRNA, and

556
00:31:36.132 --> 00:31:40.092
I would just like to remind you that most amino

557
00:31:40.132 --> 00:31:44.092
acids can be decoded by

558
00:31:44.572 --> 00:31:46.752
more than one tRNA.

559
00:31:47.572 --> 00:31:51.052
So this means that you can actually generate identical

560
00:31:51.372 --> 00:31:54.712
protein sequence with different codons.

561
00:31:56.212 --> 00:32:00.122
So today, my focus will be on the elongation

562
00:32:00.192 --> 00:32:03.652
process, but I'm also going to talk about how the

563
00:32:03.692 --> 00:32:07.492
elongation process interacts with the initiation process.

564
00:32:10.172 --> 00:32:14.152
So tRNAs, it's a fascinating molecule that I never thought I

565
00:32:14.172 --> 00:32:16.452
would study, but I ended up studying it anyways.

566
00:32:17.502 --> 00:32:21.472
And it's heavily modified, and these modifications, they affect the

567
00:32:21.552 --> 00:32:25.172
stability of the tRNA, but also, for example, the

568
00:32:25.192 --> 00:32:28.932
translational fidelity, and therefore, these modifications are

569
00:32:29.012 --> 00:32:32.972
thought to have an important role in maintaining the dynamics

570
00:32:33.012 --> 00:32:34.232
of the elongation process.

571
00:32:35.192 --> 00:32:36.672
I'm going to focus on one

572
00:32:37.532 --> 00:32:40.852
modification at the U34 position,

573
00:32:41.332 --> 00:32:44.092
which occurs in a subset of tRNAs that

574
00:32:45.392 --> 00:32:47.752
decode these codons, as you can see here.

575
00:32:48.392 --> 00:32:51.312
This modification is mediated by

576
00:32:52.292 --> 00:32:54.992
a pathway that I will refer to as the

577
00:32:56.172 --> 00:32:57.162
ELP3 pathway.

578
00:32:58.601 --> 00:33:02.112
And what you can see is that this leads to the addition of a

579
00:33:02.192 --> 00:33:06.172
relatively bulky modification at this U34 position

580
00:33:06.192 --> 00:33:06.452
here.

581
00:33:08.032 --> 00:33:11.952
So we became interested in this by coincidence when

582
00:33:12.012 --> 00:33:15.532
we saw that ELP3 is actually regulated

583
00:33:16.812 --> 00:33:18.752
via estrogen receptor signaling.

584
00:33:19.272 --> 00:33:22.852
So here you can see that depending on the activity of the estrogen

585
00:33:22.912 --> 00:33:26.652
receptor, ELP3 protein level is increased

586
00:33:27.092 --> 00:33:27.972
or decreased.

587
00:33:28.972 --> 00:33:32.592
And this also leads to changes in these

588
00:33:32.612 --> 00:33:36.592
modifications, as exemplified over here, where you can

589
00:33:36.652 --> 00:33:40.332
see that treatment with fulvestrant decreases

590
00:33:40.392 --> 00:33:43.272
the proportion of modified

591
00:33:43.332 --> 00:33:46.672
tRNA at the U34 position within the cell.

592
00:33:47.792 --> 00:33:51.312
So what we asked-- Of course, this is a complex

593
00:33:52.192 --> 00:33:55.872
experimental system where when you stimulate with estradiol

594
00:33:55.912 --> 00:33:57.101
to modulate

595
00:33:58.152 --> 00:33:59.952
estrogen receptor alpha activity.

596
00:34:00.392 --> 00:34:04.052
So we used a more simple model system where we just

597
00:34:04.112 --> 00:34:04.652
changed

598
00:34:05.872 --> 00:34:07.472
the-- So we asked what

599
00:34:08.292 --> 00:34:10.632
this pathway more specifically does

600
00:34:11.513 --> 00:34:12.592
in cancer

601
00:34:14.212 --> 00:34:17.832
cells, and we focused on hormone-dependent cancers.

602
00:34:18.872 --> 00:34:19.053
So

603
00:34:20.152 --> 00:34:23.973
first of all, you can see here that in this cell line over here, which

604
00:34:24.033 --> 00:34:27.533
is non-transformed, the expression of ELP3

605
00:34:27.632 --> 00:34:30.982
is lower relative to these cancer cell lines.

606
00:34:31.033 --> 00:34:33.882
And you can see that you can reduce the expression

607
00:34:34.812 --> 00:34:38.732
using CRISPR methods, and that this results in, again, a

608
00:34:38.772 --> 00:34:42.412
reduction, but not elimination of the modification at the

609
00:34:42.493 --> 00:34:43.712
U34 position.

610
00:34:45.652 --> 00:34:49.272
While this doesn't affect the proliferation in the

611
00:34:49.312 --> 00:34:50.462
non-transformed cells,

612
00:34:51.352 --> 00:34:52.612
it reduces

613
00:34:53.692 --> 00:34:56.332
proliferation in the transformed cells.

614
00:34:56.832 --> 00:35:00.212
And you can also see this in, for example, colony formation assays

615
00:35:01.012 --> 00:35:03.052
or organoid models of the same

616
00:35:04.472 --> 00:35:04.952
biology.

617
00:35:05.952 --> 00:35:09.872
So we wanted to understand what this modification actually does

618
00:35:10.392 --> 00:35:14.352
in this context. So to do this, we took cell

619
00:35:14.392 --> 00:35:18.072
lines that either express ELP3 or not, and we

620
00:35:18.132 --> 00:35:21.562
used a combination of proteomics and a method called polysome

621
00:35:21.572 --> 00:35:25.192
profiling that you can use to profile translation.

622
00:35:25.212 --> 00:35:29.012
So during polysome profiling, you collect mRNA that has

623
00:35:29.092 --> 00:35:32.952
many ribosomes associated with them, and then you quantify

624
00:35:32.992 --> 00:35:36.792
them. And then you can compare this to the total RNA level in the cell to

625
00:35:36.852 --> 00:35:39.632
see if the translation has changed of these mRNAs.

626
00:35:40.872 --> 00:35:44.792
So when we looked at protein levels, as expected, we could

627
00:35:44.892 --> 00:35:48.712
identify a reduction of ELP3 and also many other

628
00:35:48.732 --> 00:35:52.432
proteins. So then we used the polysome profiling

629
00:35:52.472 --> 00:35:56.432
data to try to understand the mechanisms that underlies the

630
00:35:56.452 --> 00:36:00.312
reduction in protein levels. So here is a plot where you

631
00:36:00.392 --> 00:36:04.332
compare the total mRNA changes depending on

632
00:36:04.372 --> 00:36:07.992
the ELP3 versus the levels of the translated

633
00:36:08.292 --> 00:36:10.142
mRNA or the polysome-associated RNA.

634
00:36:11.132 --> 00:36:15.072
The blue dots here are the mRNAs that encode the proteins that

635
00:36:15.112 --> 00:36:18.992
were reduced, and as you can see, they are all, or

636
00:36:19.212 --> 00:36:22.252
not all, but most of them are above this diagonal.

637
00:36:22.592 --> 00:36:25.692
So what this means is that these mRNAs

638
00:36:25.812 --> 00:36:29.452
actually have more ribosomes

639
00:36:29.532 --> 00:36:32.112
associated with them than you would expect.

640
00:36:32.792 --> 00:36:35.572
Nevertheless, they actually make less protein.

641
00:36:36.172 --> 00:36:39.632
So this is consistent with a block of elongation.

642
00:36:40.172 --> 00:36:44.144
If you compare it to the data that Ivan was showing-This

643
00:36:44.224 --> 00:36:47.424
actually, if the regulation is at the level of initiation,

644
00:36:47.984 --> 00:36:50.683
you actually expect to see more proteins if the--

645
00:36:51.704 --> 00:36:54.084
So you can probably appreciate the complexity here.

646
00:36:55.724 --> 00:36:59.604
So the idea why this happens is that if an

647
00:36:59.763 --> 00:37:03.004
mRNA has codons with a high

648
00:37:03.104 --> 00:37:06.624
requirement for these modified tRNAs, then

649
00:37:07.824 --> 00:37:11.504
reduction of these modified tRNAs would lead to poor

650
00:37:12.384 --> 00:37:13.064
elongation of these

651
00:37:14.784 --> 00:37:15.204
mRNAs.

652
00:37:16.124 --> 00:37:18.344
So we tested this simple hypothesis,

653
00:37:19.304 --> 00:37:20.344
and here you can see

654
00:37:21.344 --> 00:37:25.184
codon usage in proteins that were upregulated versus

655
00:37:25.244 --> 00:37:29.224
those that were downregulated. And then for individual amino acids, you can

656
00:37:29.284 --> 00:37:33.044
see that this codon here that

657
00:37:33.084 --> 00:37:36.944
requires a U34 modified tRNA is

658
00:37:37.024 --> 00:37:40.824
more commonly used in the proteins that were downregulated

659
00:37:40.884 --> 00:37:44.404
versus those that were up. So we could have stopped here

660
00:37:44.464 --> 00:37:47.644
essentially and said that we can explain the changes in

661
00:37:48.844 --> 00:37:52.304
the proteome, depending on tRNA modification by simply these

662
00:37:52.344 --> 00:37:56.124
codons. But the problem with this is that we don't really have a

663
00:37:56.204 --> 00:37:58.064
quantitative measurement for this.

664
00:37:58.624 --> 00:38:02.544
So we went on and used a method that

665
00:38:02.584 --> 00:38:06.404
we developed in collaboration with Ivan and his

666
00:38:06.484 --> 00:38:06.724
lab,

667
00:38:07.664 --> 00:38:11.324
called PosNet. So what PosNet does is that it uses

668
00:38:11.464 --> 00:38:15.024
many features in the RNA and tries to

669
00:38:15.064 --> 00:38:18.724
quantify their individual contribution to the regulation, but

670
00:38:18.824 --> 00:38:21.924
also how much of the regulation they actually explain.

671
00:38:22.824 --> 00:38:25.564
So when we applied this, we noticed that when we

672
00:38:25.624 --> 00:38:29.544
included these codons,

673
00:38:29.944 --> 00:38:33.184
we could actually only explain 15% of the regulation.

674
00:38:34.324 --> 00:38:37.484
And this is sort of illustrated here by this network that shows the

675
00:38:37.524 --> 00:38:38.404
different

676
00:38:39.204 --> 00:38:42.844
features of the RNA that contribute to the regulation and also

677
00:38:42.884 --> 00:38:46.684
their sort of co-occurrences, because that's another problem when studying

678
00:38:46.724 --> 00:38:50.344
these effects in translation. So

679
00:38:50.984 --> 00:38:51.884
15%

680
00:38:53.044 --> 00:38:56.464
was much less than we typically observe when we do this kind of modeling.

681
00:38:56.524 --> 00:39:00.174
So it really suggested that there might be something different than

682
00:39:00.264 --> 00:39:03.964
just simply the codon usage. And what we

683
00:39:04.004 --> 00:39:07.134
thought was that maybe it is something in the

684
00:39:07.584 --> 00:39:10.894
vicinity of the codons that also contributes

685
00:39:10.944 --> 00:39:14.824
to the regulation. So the most simple thing you can think

686
00:39:14.924 --> 00:39:18.704
of is actually a dicodon. So it's a combination of two

687
00:39:18.744 --> 00:39:22.284
codons, and of course, there are many combinations, but they're easy to study.

688
00:39:22.944 --> 00:39:26.504
So then we used another model here where we also introduced

689
00:39:26.704 --> 00:39:30.464
dicodons, and what we could see was that with the dicodons,

690
00:39:30.884 --> 00:39:34.644
we actually doubled the amount of regulation that we could

691
00:39:34.684 --> 00:39:38.024
explain. And we identified the number of dicodons that both

692
00:39:38.064 --> 00:39:41.664
associated with more protein and/or less

693
00:39:41.724 --> 00:39:45.524
protein. Interestingly, in this model, we

694
00:39:45.564 --> 00:39:49.544
can also look at how much each of the features that we

695
00:39:49.564 --> 00:39:53.364
identify contribute to the regulation independently

696
00:39:53.464 --> 00:39:55.304
of all the other features in the model.

697
00:39:55.724 --> 00:39:59.464
So here, when you look at the single codons, you can see that they can actually not

698
00:39:59.504 --> 00:40:02.024
explain anything independently of the other

699
00:40:03.004 --> 00:40:05.864
features or almost nothing. This is in contrast to the

700
00:40:05.924 --> 00:40:09.444
dicodons that seem to be better at independently

701
00:40:09.484 --> 00:40:10.744
explaining the regulation.

702
00:40:12.324 --> 00:40:15.444
Among the proteins that were

703
00:40:15.824 --> 00:40:18.944
reduced, there were six dicodons, and

704
00:40:18.984 --> 00:40:22.804
notably, they all have one codon that

705
00:40:22.844 --> 00:40:26.784
requires a U34 modified tRNA

706
00:40:27.184 --> 00:40:27.864
to be

707
00:40:29.004 --> 00:40:29.624
translated.

708
00:40:32.564 --> 00:40:33.504
When we looked at

709
00:40:34.384 --> 00:40:38.224
the number of such dicodons, you could see that the more of

710
00:40:38.284 --> 00:40:42.104
these six dicodons that you have, the more likely you

711
00:40:42.184 --> 00:40:46.044
are to see reduced protein levels, but you can also see

712
00:40:46.124 --> 00:40:48.304
that the effect seems to be relatively modest.

713
00:40:49.364 --> 00:40:50.144
Nevertheless,

714
00:40:51.704 --> 00:40:53.924
there are many of these

715
00:40:55.104 --> 00:40:58.484
mRNAs that have multiple dicodons.

716
00:40:59.184 --> 00:41:02.864
But interestingly, in contrast to just the

717
00:41:03.204 --> 00:41:03.844
U34

718
00:41:05.163 --> 00:41:06.104
codons that sort of

719
00:41:07.264 --> 00:41:10.404
correlate with the length of the coding sequence, so if you have a longer coding

720
00:41:10.464 --> 00:41:11.764
sequence, you will have more of these

721
00:41:12.984 --> 00:41:16.924
single codons. The dicodons don't correspond to the length of the coding

722
00:41:16.984 --> 00:41:17.424
sequence.

723
00:41:19.004 --> 00:41:22.904
So therefore, we thought that maybe there is another factor here,

724
00:41:23.004 --> 00:41:24.984
which is the distance between the dicodons.

725
00:41:25.494 --> 00:41:28.544
And what we could see was that when we looked at those

726
00:41:29.684 --> 00:41:33.524
mRNAs that had the dicodons closest, we could see a more

727
00:41:33.624 --> 00:41:37.204
strong reduction in protein levels than those that had the

728
00:41:37.244 --> 00:41:38.564
dicodons far apart.

729
00:41:40.284 --> 00:41:44.204
And this is illustrated here. So actually this subset here, the

730
00:41:44.224 --> 00:41:46.804
dicodons are very close. So they're only 18 nucleotides

731
00:41:47.404 --> 00:41:51.034
apart, median. So this suggests that it's

732
00:41:51.304 --> 00:41:55.144
not just the dicodons, it's really the context that they

733
00:41:55.204 --> 00:41:55.644
are in.

734
00:41:56.824 --> 00:42:00.564
And of course, when you look at this, you

735
00:42:00.624 --> 00:42:01.364
realize that

736
00:42:02.844 --> 00:42:06.564
although there is a sort of statistical difference here,

737
00:42:07.124 --> 00:42:11.004
there's a lot of variation. So we thought that maybe these contexts can

738
00:42:11.044 --> 00:42:14.804
help us to understand why some of the mRNAs here are more

739
00:42:15.704 --> 00:42:16.644
affected than others.

740
00:42:17.664 --> 00:42:21.604
So to do this, again, we used this modeling, but

741
00:42:21.644 --> 00:42:25.464
we used the local sequence features, so meaning the features

742
00:42:25.564 --> 00:42:29.544
that are around these dicodons. So interestingly,

743
00:42:29.764 --> 00:42:33.684
we could of course find some features that

744
00:42:33.744 --> 00:42:34.684
related to the

745
00:42:35.744 --> 00:42:39.344
elongation process and features in the coding

746
00:42:39.404 --> 00:42:41.924
sequence. But we also found many

747
00:42:42.904 --> 00:42:46.604
features that were in the 5 prime UTR, which was kind of unexpected

748
00:42:46.664 --> 00:42:48.024
because we were looking at

749
00:42:48.064 --> 00:42:51.878
elongation.So we wondered,

750
00:42:52.458 --> 00:42:56.448
does this mean that mRNAs that have these dicodons, do

751
00:42:56.488 --> 00:42:59.868
they also have a sort of distinct translation initiation

752
00:42:59.908 --> 00:43:03.648
activity? And what we could see was that the more

753
00:43:03.688 --> 00:43:07.348
dicodons that an mRNA had, the

754
00:43:07.428 --> 00:43:10.928
less efficient translation initiation it has.

755
00:43:11.038 --> 00:43:14.468
So these mRNAs seem to be protected

756
00:43:14.528 --> 00:43:18.348
against having too many ribosomes loaded on the mRNA at the

757
00:43:18.388 --> 00:43:21.928
same time. And Ivan talked about the length of

758
00:43:21.968 --> 00:43:25.808
the 5' UTR. Indeed, we could see that those mRNAs that

759
00:43:25.888 --> 00:43:29.528
have several of these dicodons, they also had

760
00:43:29.688 --> 00:43:33.308
longer 5' UTRs, which is typically associated with less efficient

761
00:43:33.468 --> 00:43:34.108
translation.

762
00:43:36.588 --> 00:43:38.228
When we look at the function of the

